1)What are the project’s goals? If you’re hired as a data/business analyst to predict how well a movie will perform in theaters, what kind of data would you collect? What variables are highly correlated to imdb score? In this project, you will use imdb_score to measure a movie’s success.¶

The movie industry needs a better way of predicting what movies will be successful or not.They spend millions of dollars every year on finding a better prediction model to direct the money to a better movie. The projects goal is to find a more accurate model that predicts which movie will create a larger revenue. The data I would collect to see how well a movie will perform in theaters The variables that are similar to the IMDB score would be gross, movie_facebook_likes, director_name, and budget¶

# Here we read in our csv again and call it as data
# Next we create an array of all of the columns that we feel are important to keep. 
# We then set 'English' and 'USA' as a filler for null values in the dataframe. 

# This cleaning code is courtesy of https://github.com/tousif101/MoviePredictor/blob/master/movie_data_clean.py
import random

data = pd.read_csv("C:\\Users\\mitchell Hogan\\Desktop\\665\\movie_metadata.csv", index_col=False)

keep_col = ['director_name', 'num_critic_for_reviews', 'duration', 'director_facebook_likes',
            'actor_1_facebook_likes', 'gross', 'genres', 'actor_1_name', 'movie_title',
            'num_voted_users', 'cast_total_facebook_likes', 'num_user_for_reviews', 'language',
            'country', 'content_rating', 'budget', 'title_year', 'imdb_score', 'movie_facebook_likes']

new_file = data[keep_col]

new_data = new_file.fillna(new_file.mean())

new_data = new_data[new_data.language == 'English']
new_data = new_data[new_data.country == 'USA']

new_data = new_data[new_data.content_rating != 'TV-14']
new_data = new_data[new_data.content_rating != 'TV-PG']
new_data = new_data[new_data.content_rating != 'TV-MA']
new_data = new_data[new_data.content_rating != 'TV-G']
new_data = new_data[new_data.content_rating != 'TV-Y7']
new_data = new_data[new_data.content_rating != 'Passed']
new_data = new_data[new_data.content_rating != 'Approved']
new_data = new_data[new_data.content_rating != 'Not Rated']
new_data = new_data[new_data.content_rating != 'Unrated']
new_data = new_data[new_data.content_rating != 'NC-17']
new_data = new_data[pd.notnull(new_data['content_rating'])]

new_data = new_data.reset_index()

for i in range(0, len(new_data['genres'])):
    record = new_data.loc[i, 'genres']
    splitVal = record.split('|')
    val = random.choice(splitVal)
    new_data.iloc[i, new_data.columns.get_loc('genres')] = val

new_data = new_data.reset_index()

cleaned_data = new_data

cleaned_data.to_csv("cleaned_movie_metadata.csv",index =False)
df = cleaned_data
# This cleaning code is courtesy of https://github.com/tousif101/MoviePredictor/blob/master/movie_data_clean.py

    kmeans_model = KMeans(n_clusters=k, random_state=1).fit(X)
    labels = kmeans_model.labels_
    print metrics.silhouette_score(X, labels, metric='euclidean')

Storytelling¶
















Regression:¶
















The whole use of the regression models is to understand which independent variables are related to the dependent variables. In this data set we are analyzing different categorical variables about movies. The biggest categorical variable is imdb_score. This variable was my focus in the regression model section. 
While using different regression model methods I found that randomforestRegressor gave me a r-squared prediction of 41% . The Lasso Regression model gave me a r-squared prediction of 76% and the Linear Regression model gave me a r-square of 79% percent. The model that I would go with is the Linear Regression model because the higher the r-square in a regression model means that the model explains all the variability of the data around its mean. This means that this model is a realtionship between my model and response variable.

















Classification:¶
















Classification model is designed to classify data into certain classes. For this section I used Random Forest Classification, Decision Tree, KNN, and Logistic. My random Forest Classification predictive score was 73%. My Decision Tree score was 69%. My KNN score 52%. Finally my logistic score was 63%. Therefore my model with the best accuracy was the Random Forest Classification. 
Certain predictors were found to be better at finding the better movie. imdb_score, gross,budget, duration, and content_rating. I classified this these categories into a bin called "category". These categories in my mind where the most important factors in what it takes for a movie to be successful.

















Clustering¶
















Clustering is designed to group similar categorical variables together to see there pattern of behavior.The first model I used was the hierarchical clustering which  looks at what forms cluster and the distance that is apart from these clusters. 
*Looking at my Hierarchical Clustering I notice that cluster one cluster around the num_critic_for_reviews and duration.


*K-means is all about clustering the data into other cluster that have the nearest mean. In this data set I determined that the zero cluster had the most members that had the closet mean and that was 2596.

















The variables that relate to imdb_score are gross, num_facebook_likes, and duration. After analyzing the data from the dataset I was able to determine that num_voted_users and num_user_for_reviews were both strong indicators of profit and success.¶
















6) Summary¶
















* After looking at different tests, graphs, and grouping of data I have determined some key factors of what it takes for a movie to be successful.¶
* After analyzing the data from the dataset I was able to determine that num_voted_users and num_user_for_reviews were both strong indicators of profit and success.¶
















* Another observation I found was that the highest imbd score did not associate with the biggest gross profit. There was actually a sweet spot around 7.5-8. This lead to the biggest gross profit.¶
















* I found it interesting that most of the Imbd_scores were actually between 1-2 instead of in the 4-6 range.¶
















* After looking at the budget, imbd_scores, and gross I saw a correlation that high number of critic reviews in the 8.8-9 range. I also saw that if the duration was longer the imbd.score tended to be higher.¶
















*Looking at the business intelligence I really wanted to look at the realitonship between the imdb_score and gross. I wanted to see what type of realtionship there is between gross profit and the imdb_score associated with it. After analyzing it wiht different graphs and plots I saw that there is a trend where the higher the imdb score, that generally the gross would be higher.¶
















* I also wanted to see if the gross and budget had a positive realtionship. It barley has a positive realtionship. After looking at the graph I determine that just because a film has a high budget it doesn't produce a top grossing film¶
















* I cleaned up the null values in gross, aspect_ratio, and budget,  I replaced them with the mean values for each category. I was going to remove the null values in the dataset but this would get rid of a majority of the data and would complete change the results.¶
















* The whole point of this project was to find a way to predict a movie success, After analyzing the different graphs and data comparisons, I came to the conclusion that there is a higher correlation for gross profits, if your movie is high in num_voted_users, num_user_for_reviews, imbd_score and director_name. This variables all lead to a higher grossing film than any other variables.¶
